    <text>
        <body>
            <head>271. Memorandum From the Chairman of the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah"
                    >Joint Chiefs of Staff</orgName> (<persName corresp="recusSiT3UbixAWkn"
                    >Crowe</persName>) to the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (<persName corresp="recgt3SoCfObWa7Tt">Powell</persName>)<note n="1"
                    place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d271fn1">Source: Reagan Library, System IV
                    Files, 1988 SYS IV <gloss target="#t_RWR_1">RWR</gloss> INT 40051-40073. Top
                    Secret.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1988-02-19"
                        >February 19, 1988</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>
                    <gloss target="#t_PFIAB_1">
                        <orgName corresp="recadxMxnHKQXZmiU">PFIAB</orgName>
                    </gloss> Letter to President Regarding <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs>
                    (U)</item>
            </list>
            <p>1. (TS) You asked<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d271fn2">Assistant to the President
                    for National Security Affairs memorandum, 11 February 1988, subject as above.
                    [Footnote is in the original text]</note> for my comments on <persName
                    corresp="recTv24KjXFdhanyt">Anne Armstrong</persName>’s recent <gloss
                    target="#t_PFIAB_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recadxMxnHKQXZmiU">PFIAB</orgName>
                </gloss> letter to the President<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d271fn3">See <ref
                        target="#d262">Document 262</ref>.</note> regarding the proposed <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs>. The <gloss
                    target="#t_PFIAB_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recadxMxnHKQXZmiU">PFIAB</orgName>
                </gloss> assessment provides a sobering preview of the hard, expansive <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recpJMerwIQpQmCmI">ratification</rs> challenge that a
                    <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">treaty</rs> will face.
                It reinforces my judgment that we cannot afford to cut corners in trying to
                accelerate work toward a <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement. Getting the details right is critical. No matter how good the
                framework of limits and restrictions, unless that framework is supported by an
                acceptable network of definitions, <rs type="topic" corresp="recTaee7UxoGjTDrc"
                    >counting rules</rs>, inspection procedures, and so forth, we will not be able
                to answer to our satisfaction the sorts of fundamental questions that the <gloss
                    target="#t_PFIAB_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recadxMxnHKQXZmiU">PFIAB</orgName>
                </gloss> raises. Nor will we be able to answer the critics. You will <pb facs="1242"
                    n="1215" xml:id="pg_1215"/> recall that one of the most elusive <rs
                    corresp="recMjLDCnI9cLa32M" type="topic">compliance</rs> debates on <gloss
                    target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss> involved the details of the definition of a new type of light <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>, and how the Soviets exploited that definition in deploying the <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recMS3hu34UIPBB1l">SS–25</rs>. At this point in <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>, we still lack, within the US <rs type="event" corresp="recrvfeHjk0YIZ1si"
                    >Government</rs>, an agreed approach to distinguishing existing from future
                types of <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>. That
                is the sort of detail of which there are dozens that must be nailed down
                satisfactorily as we proceed.</p>
            <p>2. (TS) Turning to the general themes that <persName corresp="recTv24KjXFdhanyt">Anne
                    Armstrong</persName> raises, clearly the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah"
                    >Joint Chiefs of Staff</orgName> are not yet in a position to pass judgment on
                the effective verifiability or the certified military sufficiency of a completed
                    <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement for the simple reason that so many details remain to be worked
                out. Thus far the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Joint Chiefs of
                    Staff</orgName> have concluded that the framework for approaching <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> reductions is sound. I am concerned with the resource issues that <persName
                    corresp="recTv24KjXFdhanyt">Anne Armstrong</persName> raises. In their 12 May
                1987 memorandum to your predecessor,<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d271fn4"
                    >Scheduled for publication in <ref target="frus1981-88v12">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. XII,
                        Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty, 1984–1988</ref>.</note> on <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recvy4qghNg7RFWmN">intermediate-range nuclear
                    forces</rs>, the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Joint Chiefs of
                    Staff</orgName> advised that “the American public should be prepared for the
                fact that a sound <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="reclckIw9AgH05Yxw">INF</rs>
                </gloss> agreement will not save money. The cost of effective <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>, particularly if
                residual <gloss target="#t_LRINF_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="reczU3lVS4eZr8vxf">LRINF</rs>
                </gloss> and/or <rs type="topic" corresp="rec43jYPGDcX0aJRW">SRINF</rs> are
                maintained, and of compensatory security measures will be quite considerable. It is
                strongly recommended that the political leadership begin conveying this message
                early and clearly.” The potential costs of <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="reclckIw9AgH05Yxw">INF</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs> pale in comparison
                with what is under consideration for <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>.</p>
            <p>3. (S) The <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Joint Chiefs of Staff</orgName> have
                devoted hundreds of hours of discussion and study to <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> over the past several years. This <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recrvfeHjk0YIZ1si">Administration</rs> has made considerable progress
                toward a sound <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement. With deliberative, well-conceived answers to the remaining hard
                questions, that progress can be carried forward. Above all else, we must not cut
                corners.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recusSiT3UbixAWkn">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">William J. Crowe, Jr.</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Chairman<lb/>
                        <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Joint Chiefs of Staff</orgName>
                    </hi>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
